@K just memorize the values of trig function for certain values - 0, 30, 45, 60, 90, 120, 180, 270, 360 and the formulas/identities for conversion, and remember which function is negative for what quadrant. I myself never memorized the unit circle, but if you ask me what's the value of cos(270)?I can tell you that it's 0 and that cos(270+x) is equal to sin(x) by conversion. which just implies that cos(270) = sin(0) by conversion which is indeed true, both are 0.

One more thing, you can always look up the values, and maybe in your country there isn't much need for memorizing all of that, but here we do. And it's helps a *ton* in calculus.

**you can use angles in radians, that's more easy. I just can't write pi in text.

@K well if you aren't comfortable with trigonometry and the unit circle, calculus is gonna be hard for you.

If you are self learning, I'd suggest making your algebra(functions), coordinate, and trigonometry strong before even trying to touch calculus.

You can start it even if you have a mild understanding of all that, but that won't get you any far, you'll be stuck somewhere on the track pretty soon. Not something I would recommend at all.
